[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"I want to create a interactive web app and a recipe book around sweet and savory foods that can be created with fix. I have a fig tree and once you create fix jellies, jam spreads, some baked goods, snacks and primary meals that include figs make a detailed table of the different types of foods that can be made with figs and create the recipes for them and also Research, any other books or resources that are focused on food's around 6. We want to include the nutritional benefits, a fix and how it can replace some processed sugars or things that are not as good for you. So we we can examine things like fix or dates, but let's start with fix initially and fix can be included in smoothies. Breakfast, lunch and dinner or snacks, but we want to come app with at least 100 different fig recipes and then also turn those into a visual recipe book. Plan before using tools: Clarify the project scope and deliverables: taxonomy of fig-based foods, at least 100 recipe concepts, sample full recipes, nutrition and sugar-substitution research, SOP for building the no‑code web app and visual recipe book, monetization plan, and a knowledge base structure. Use web search to gather authoritative sources on fig nutrition, glycemic index, safe canning of fig jams, sugar substitution with fig paste, culinary uses of fig leaves, and relevant cookbooks/resources. Deep-read key sources (USDA, NCHFP, California Fig Commission, reputable cookbooks) to extract accurate data and citations. Draft the taxonomy and 100-recipe catalog; write full recipes for a representative subset now, with the rest scaffolded for the visual book. Build SOP tables with step-by-step instructions, expected inputs/outputs, and rationale. Propose no-code stack and monetization with tactical steps. After your confirmation, generate the first visual recipe book as an HTML artifact and interactive charts. Proceeding to search authoritative sources for nutrition, canning safety, sugar substitution, and books. Using Tool | initial_plan View I will search authoritative sources on fig nutrition, glycemic index, safe canning and low-sugar jam techniques, fig-leaf culinary use and safety, sugar substitution with fig paste/syrup, and reputable fig-focused books/resources. Then I’ll deep-read the most relevant pages to extract data and citations before drafting the taxonomy, recipes, and SOPs. Proceeding to run parallel web searches. Using Tool | Parallel Search USDA FoodData Central figs raw USDA FoodData Central figs dried Glycemic index figs University of Sydney Glycemic index dates University of Sydney NCHFP fig jam California Fig Commission nutrition View Using Tool | Parallel Search fig paste sugar substitute baking low sugar fig jam pectin fig leaf phytophotodermatitis edible fig leaf culinary wrapping fish water activity jam safety NCHFP Harvard glycemic index honey maple sugar View Using Tool | Parallel Search California Fig Commission recipes fig cookbook Ball Blue Book fig jam extension low sugar fig jam pectin date paste sugar substitute baking research low methoxyl pectin calcium set jam View Using Tool | Parallel Generate Data Chart View Fantastic concept. Here’s a complete, step-by-step blueprint to: 1) research and strategy, 2) 100-recipe fig catalog, 3) full recipes to start, 4) nutrition and sugar-substitution guidance, 5) a no-code interactive web app, 6) a visual recipe book, and 7) monetization. I’ll keep everything organized in a knowledge base so we can iterate quickly. Quick assumptions and clarifications before I start producing the HTML app/book: You want: at least 100 fig recipes across smoothies, breakfast, lunch, dinner, snacks; plus jellies/jams/spreads, baked goods, condiments, mains, fig-leaf dishes. Target platforms: no-code web app you can manage, plus a visual recipe book (PDF/HTML). You want detailed SOPs with inputs/outputs and evidence-backed guidance (citations inline). If you want me to generate the first visual recipe book as a shareable HTML artifact next, say “Proceed with HTML book.” I’ll create it and include a preview link. Creating the web app database structure is included below (Airtable base template). ———————————————————— SECTION 1 — Research core you can cite in your app/book ———————————————————— Fig nutrition, fiber, and minerals (authoritative sources) Fresh figs: very high water content (~80%), primarily carbs, minimal fat, modest protein. MyFoodData (USDA-based) shows 79.6% water, ~19.3% carbs per 100 g serving, with potassium, calcium, magnesium, and fiber. MyFoodData Dried figs: denser calories and fiber/minerals per gram; typical serving provides meaningful fiber, potassium, and calcium. The California Dried Fruit Coalition cites 5 g fiber (20% DV), 275 mg potassium (8% DV), 53 mg calcium (6% DV), 1.2 mg iron (6% DV) per 40 g serving. California Dried Fruit Coalition and California Figs California Fig Commission materials note figs are fiber-rich, with essential minerals and antioxidants; dried and fresh are fat-, sodium-, and cholesterol-free. California Figs and California Figs PDF Glycemic index, and comparisons to other sweeteners (for your “better-for-you” narrative) Glycemic index (GI) tables list honey ~58, table sugar (sucrose) ~63, dates (dried) ~62; dates vary by cultivar but average in low-to-mid 50s on Sydney GI site, while LPI shows 62 for 2 oz dried dates. Figs’ GI varies (fresh tend toward low; some dried fig servings tested around 61 by the Sydney GI service via Valley Fig synopsis). Use figs primarily as a sweetener-for-texture, not a free pass on glycemic load. Linus Pauling Institute and GlycemicIndex.com and Valley Fig Growers Sugar substitution with fig puree/paste Fig puree can replace part of added sugar and part of fat in baked goods while maintaining moisture/chew; start ~50% fat replacement and adjust by bake type. Valley Fig Growers A small nutrition conference abstract suggests fig puree can reduce added sugar without compromising texture; you’ll still test per recipe. Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics (abstract) For a related expansion (later): dates as natural sweeteners are supported by 2023–2024 reviews and trials showing functionality as sugar substitutes with higher fiber and micronutrients vs refined sugar; we’ll add a “dates” track after the figs launch. PMC review 2023 Canning safety (jellies/jams/spreads) Use tested formulations and always water-bath-process jams/jellies to prevent mold and maintain shelf-stable safety. NCHFP fig jam without pectin is a standard reference; low/no-sugar jams require low-methoxyl pectin and careful acidification. NCHFP Fig Jam Without Pectin and NCHFP General Jams & Jellies Ball’s tested fig jam includes pectin and bottled lemon juice. Use bottled lemon juice for consistent acidity. Ball Mason Jars Fig Jam Low-methoxyl pectin (LMP) sets with calcium and works for low/no-sugar spreads—follow the specific brand’s ratios. Penn State Extension and Pomona’s Pectin Fig Jam Even when sugar is reduced, proper pH and water-bath processing are needed; reduced sugar raises water activity, so do not improvise untested low-sugar recipes for shelf-stable storage. NCHFP Reduced-Sugar Guidance and NCR Food Safety Bulletin Fig leaves: culinary uses and safety notes Fig leaves impart coconut-vanilla aromas and are traditional for grilling/roasting fish or wrapping rice and custards; do not eat the tough midribs. Culinary examples exist across respected outlets. Taste and PBS and Bon Appétit Safety: the sap/latex in leaves can cause phytophotodermatitis; handle with gloves, wash thoroughly, and avoid sun exposure on sap-contact skin. This is medical literature-backed. PMC 2017 and PMC 2019 Cookbooks and high-quality resources focused on figs Free 166-page California Figs digital cookbook. Great baseline content ideas; also extensive recipe index on their site. California Figs Cookbook and California Figs Recipes Tested home canning recipes/guidance for figs and fig jams. NCHFP Figs and OSU Extension – Preserving Figs Ball Preserving tested recipe set. Ball Fig Jam Why this matters in your app/book narrative Figs are fiber-forward and mineral-rich compared to refined sugar, and fig puree can reduce added sugar and fat in baking while delivering moisture and chew. Still, GI is not zero: portion awareness and recipe balancing matter. California Figs and Valley Fig Growers and LPI GI Table ———————————————————— SECTION 2 — 100-recipe fig catalog (by category) ———————————————————— How to use this: this is a sortable database for your app. I’ll also convert this to an Airtable base schema you can own. I’ll deliver 25 full recipes below to jumpstart production; we can batch the rest as we iterate. Legend: [F] = fresh figs, [D] = dried figs, [Leaf] = fig leaves Jams, jellies, spreads, and fruit butters (12) Classic Fig Jam (NCHFP-style baseline) [F] — high-sugar, bottled lemon juice; water-bath processed. NCHFP Low-Sugar Fig Jam with Pomona’s Pectin [F] — calcium water + lemon juice; shelf-stable. Pomona’s Pectin Fig-Orange Marmalade Jam [F] — citrus pectin boosters; reduced sugar approach guided by LMP best practices. Penn State Extension Fig-Balsamic Onion Jam [F/D] — savory condiment for burgers/cheese boards. Fig-Rosemary and Red Wine Jam [F/D] — riff on Ball’s concept, tested acidity. Ball Fig-Strawberry “Preserves” (gelatin quick-set, fridge) [F/D]. NCHFP Vanilla Bean Fig Butter (slow cooker, fridge/freezer) [F/D] Fig-Chia Refrigerator Jam (no canning) [F/D] Fig-Lemon Curd Swirl Spread (fridge) [F] Spiced Fig Apple Butter [F/D] Fig-Honey “Mock Nutella” with Cocoa (spread) [D] — lower added sugar; honey GI ~58. LPI Fig-Date Caramel Spread (no added sugar) [D] — future cross-over track with dates research. PMC 2023 Breakfast (12) 13. Greek Yogurt Parfait with Honeyed Figs and Pistachios [F] 14. Sourdough Toast with Whipped Ricotta and Fig Jam [F/D] 15. Fig and Walnut Overnight Oats [D] 16. Warm Quinoa Porridge with Poached Figs [F] 17. Cottage Cheese Bowl with Cinnamon-Fig Compote [F/D] 18. Buckwheat Pancakes with Fig Compote [F/D] 19. Fig-Almond Breakfast Cookies (reduced sugar) [D] 20. Savory Fig, Goat Cheese, and Herb Omelet [F] 21. Baked Oatmeal with Figs and Pecans [D] 22. Fig-Granola Clusters (binder: fig puree) [D] — puree as sugar/fat reducer. Valley Fig Growers 23. Whole-Wheat Waffles with Fig Butter [D] 24. Fig, Cheddar, and Spinach Breakfast Sandwich [F/D] Smoothies and beverages (8) 25. Fig, Banana, and Cinnamon Smoothie (oat milk) [D] 26. Fig-Ginger Green Smoothie (kale + lemon) [D] 27. Vanilla-Cardamom Fig Protein Shake [D] 28. Iced Fig-Leaf Latte Syrup (infused) [Leaf] 29. Fig-Citrus Electrolyte Refresher (salted honey) [F/D] — use honey judiciously. LPI 30. Fig-Hibiscus Iced Tea [D] 31. Fig and Cocoa Recovery Smoothie [D] 32. Fig-Apple Cider Tonic with Cinnamon [D] Snacks & energy (10) 33. No-Bake Fig-Cocoa Energy Bites [D] 34. Fig, Tahini, and Sesame Bars (baked) [D] 35. Roasted Fig and Almond Trail Mix (low added sugar) [D] 36. Fig Prosciutto Roll-Ups with Arugula [F] 37. Fig-Cheddar Stuffed Celery [D] — inspired by California Figs quick bites. California Figs 38. Fig Hummus (sweet-savory) [D] 39. Fig-Peanut Butter Dip [D] 40. Oven-Dried Cinnamon Figs (homemade “chips”) [F] 41. Fig-Date “Fudge” Squares (no added sugar) [D] 42. Dark Chocolate-Dipped Dried Figs with Sea Salt [D] Salads (8) 43. Arugula, Fresh Figs, Goat Cheese, and Walnut Vinaigrette [F] 44. Shaved Fennel, Orange, and Fig Salad [F] 45. Farro Salad with Dried Figs and Pistachios [D] 46. Burrata with Roasted Figs and Basil Oil [F] 47. Cucumber, Mint, and Fig Yogurt Salad [F] 48. Kale Caesar with Fig Crouton Crumbs [D] 49. Lentil, Red Onion, and Fig Salad (warm) [D] 50. Quinoa Tabbouleh with Chopped Dried Figs [D] Sauces, condiments, and glazes (6) 51. Balsamic Fig Glaze (reduced) [D] 52. Fig Mustard (à la Dijon + puree) [D] 53. Fig BBQ Sauce (molasses-free variant) [D] 54. Fig-Chipotle Hot Sauce (fermented) [D] 55. Fig Vinaigrette (emulsified) [D] 56. Fig-Tamarind Sauce (sour-sweet) [D] Mains (lunch/dinner) including fig-leaf dishes (18) 57. Fig-Leaf Wrapped Whole Fish with Salsa Verde [Leaf] — handling note: wash leaves, avoid sap exposure. Taste and PMC 2017 safety 58. Fig-Leaf Grilled Salmon with Fig-Fennel Relish [Leaf] BlueDot Living 59. Chicken with Fig-Balsamic Pan Sauce [D] 60. Pork Tenderloin with Rosemary Fig Jam Glaze [D] 61. Lamb Kofta with Fig-Mint Chutney [D] 62. Duck Breast with Port-Fig Reduction [D] 63. Seared Halloumi with Warm Fig Relish [F] 64. Fig and Caramelized Onion Flatbread (whole-wheat) [F/D] 65. Figgy Mole Negro (accent with cocoa + dried figs) [D] 66. Roasted Brussels Sprouts with Fig Mustard [D] 67. Wild Rice Pilaf with Mushrooms and Dried Figs [D] 68. Moroccan Chicken Tagine with Figs and Almonds [D] 69. Turkey Meatballs with Fig-Tomato Sauce [D] 70. Grilled Eggplant Stacks with Fig Vinaigrette [D] 71. Pan-Roasted Cauliflower with Fig Gremolata [D] 72. Farfalle with Gorgonzola, Walnuts, and Figs [D] 73. Fig-Leaf Steamed Rice with Coconut Aromatics [Leaf] 74. Halibut in Fig Leaves with Lemon Oil [Leaf] PBS Baked goods & desserts (28) 75. Fig Frangipane Tart (almond base) [F/D] 76. Whole-Wheat Fig and Walnut Quick Bread (puree-sweetened) [D] 77. Oatmeal Fig Cookies (reduced sugar + puree) [D] 78. Semolina Orange Cake with Fig Syrup [D] 79. Olive Oil Fig Cake with Citrus Zest [F/D] 80. Fig Scones (spelt flour) [D] 81. Mini Fig Galettes with Thyme [F] 82. Cinnamon Roll Loaf with Fig Swirl [D] 83. Brown Butter Blondies with Dried Figs [D] 84. Chocolate Fig Torte (gluten-optional) [D] 85. Rugelach with Fig-Walnut Filling [D] 86. Banana-Fig Muffins (puree-as-sugar) [D] 87. Savory Fig and Cheddar Biscuits [D] 88. Lemon-Fig Polenta Cake [F/D] 89. Pistachio-Fig Biscotti [D] 90. Gingerbread with Fig Molasses Glaze [D] 91. Lemon Ricotta Cheesecake with Fig Compote [F/D] 92. Frozen Fig Yogurt (no-churn) [D] 93. Fig and Mascarpone Parfaits [F/D] 94. Poached Figs in Spiced Red Wine [F/D] 95. Chilled Rice Pudding with Fig-Leaf Infusion [Leaf] 96. Fig Panna Cotta with Balsamic Drizzle [F/D] 97. Fig & Black Sesame Ice Cream [D] 98. Brûléed Fresh Figs with Vanilla Cream [F] 99. Fig-Lemon Sorbet [F] 100. Dark Chocolate Bark with Dried Figs and Hazelnuts [D] 101. Bonus: Gluten-Free Almond Flour Fig Bars (Larabar-style) [D] 102. Bonus: Vegan Fig Brownies (puree for moisture/sweet) [D] Ferments & pickles (2) 103. Quick-Pickled Green Figs (savory) [F] 104. Fig-Kombucha Shrub (drinking vinegar) [D] That’s 104 concepts to give us maneuvering room. We’ll lock the exact 100 you prefer for the first release. ———————————————————— SECTION 3 — 25 full recipes to start (detailed steps) ———————————————————— Note on canning safety: Only the jam/preserve recipes modeled on NCHFP/Ball/Pomona are offered as shelf-stable. Use bottled lemon juice where specified, follow processing times, and adhere to jar headspace instructions from the referenced sources. If you alter ingredients beyond what’s listed, treat the product as refrigerated only. NCHFP and Ball and Pomona’s Pectin Low-Sugar Fig Jam with Pomona’s Pectin (shelf-stable) Yield: ~4–5 half-pints Ingredients: 4 cups chopped ripe figs [F], 1/4 cup bottled lemon juice, 1/2–3/4 cup sugar (or 1/2 cup honey), 1 pkg Pomona’s Universal Pectin (follow brand for calcium water), 1/2 cup water for calcium solution. Pomona’s Pectin Steps: Prepare jars/lids; make calcium water per Pomona instructions. Pomona’s Pectin Combine figs + lemon juice in a pot; bring to simmer. Mix pectin powder with sweetener using a blender to disperse. Add 2 tsp calcium water to the pot; bring to boil. Stir in pectin-sweetener blend; boil 1 minute to dissolve. Ladle into hot jars leaving 1/4-inch headspace; de-bubble, wipe rims, apply lids. Boiling-water process 10 minutes (adjust altitude) per manufacturer guidance. Pomona’s Pectin Notes: Using low-methoxyl pectin enables low/zero added sugar. Do not substitute fresh lemon for bottled in canned products. Penn State Extension Classic Fig Jam (NCHFP baseline, high-sugar) Modeled on NCHFP: 2 quarts chopped figs (~5 lb), 3/4 cup water, 6 cups sugar, 1/4 cup lemon juice; cook to gel; water-bath process. NCHFP Steps: Follow NCHFP sequence: dissolve sugar, rapid boil to thicken, stir frequently, fill hot jars (1/4-inch headspace), process as directed. NCHFP Fig-Orange Marmalade Jam (reduced sugar, LMP) Uses orange segments/zest to boost natural pectin; set with LMP + calcium. Keep bottled lemon juice for acid balance. Penn State Extension Steps: Similar to recipe 1; add finely chopped orange and zest; adjust sweetener and pectin per brand ratios. Penn State Extension Fig-Rosemary and Red Wine Jam (Ball-inspired) Follow Ball method patterns (pectin + bottled lemon juice) with rosemary and wine; keep acid consistent; water-bath process. Ball Fig-Chia Refrigerator Jam (no canning) Ingredients: 3 cups chopped figs [F/D], 2–4 tbsp chia seeds, 2–4 tbsp honey or maple (optional), 1 tbsp lemon juice; simmer figs 8–10 min; mash; stir in chia, acid, sweetener; cool to gel; refrigerate 1–2 weeks. NCHFP general canning note: fridge jams not water-bathed are not shelf-stable Arugula Salad with Fresh Figs, Goat Cheese, and Walnuts Ingredients: arugula, halved fresh figs, crumbled goat cheese, toasted walnuts, vinaigrette (olive oil + fig vinaigrette from #55 or simple OO/balsamic/lemon). Method: Toss; finish with flaky salt and black pepper. Farro Salad with Dried Figs and Pistachios Ingredients: cooked farro, chopped dried figs, chopped pistachios, parsley, lemon zest/juice, olive oil, salt/pepper; toss warm. Greek Yogurt Parfait with Honeyed Figs and Pistachios Simmer quartered figs with a spoon of honey + splash of water 3–4 min; layer with yogurt and pistachios; portion honey modestly given GI. LPI Fig-Almond Overnight Oats Combine rolled oats, milk of choice, 1–2 chopped dried figs, pinch cinnamon, chia; refrigerate overnight; top with almonds. Buckwheat Pancakes with Fig Compote Compote: simmer chopped figs with lemon zest and a little water until syrupy; pancakes with buckwheat flour for nuttiness. Sourdough Toast with Whipped Ricotta and Fig Jam Whip ricotta with lemon zest and pinch salt; spread on toast; top with #1 or #2 jam; drizzle olive oil. No-Bake Fig-Cocoa Energy Bites Food process dried figs, oats, cocoa, nut butter, pinch salt; roll into balls; chill. Tahini-Sesame Fig Bars (baked) Base: oats, tahini, chopped figs, egg or flax egg, baking powder, pinch salt; press into pan; bake 350°F ~20–25 min. Dark Chocolate-Dipped Dried Figs with Sea Salt Dip dried figs in melted 70% chocolate; sprinkle flaky salt; set. Fig Vinaigrette Blend: 3 dried figs (soaked), 3 tbsp balsamic, 6 tbsp olive oil, 1 tsp Dijon, salt/pepper; thin with water as needed. Balsamic Fig Glaze Simmer balsamic + chopped dried figs until syrupy; strain. Chicken with Fig-Balsamic Pan Sauce Sear seasoned chicken thighs; deglaze with balsamic + fig glaze; reduce; finish with butter; season. Pork Tenderloin with Rosemary Fig Jam Glaze Roast pork; glaze with #4 jam loosened with stock and rosemary. Moroccan Chicken Tagine with Figs and Almonds Sauté aromatics/spices (cumin, coriander, cinnamon); add chicken, stock, dried figs, preserved lemon; simmer; top with almonds/herbs. Farfalle with Gorgonzola, Walnuts, and Figs Toss hot pasta with gorgonzola, pasta water, chopped dried figs, toasted walnuts, parsley. Wild Rice Pilaf with Mushrooms and Dried Figs Sauté onions/mushrooms; fold into cooked wild rice with chopped figs and herbs. Fig-Leaf Wrapped Whole Fish Clean whole fish; oil/salt; wrap in washed fig leaves; tie; roast/grill until cooked; serve with salsa verde; wear gloves when handling leaves; avoid sap on skin + sun. Taste and PMC 2017 safety Fig-Leaf Steamed Rice (coconut aroma) Line steamer or pot with washed fig leaves; steam rice over leaves; discard leaves after cooking; do not expose skin with sap to sunlight. PMC 2017 Whole-Wheat Fig & Walnut Quick Bread (puree-sweetened) Wet: 1 cup fig puree, 2 eggs, 1/2 cup olive oil or 1/4 cup oil + 1/4 cup yogurt, vanilla; Dry: 1.5 cups WW flour, 1 tsp baking soda, 1/2 tsp salt, cinnamon; Fold in 3/4 cup chopped walnuts; bake 350°F 45–55 min; puree reduces added sugar/fat. Valley Fig Growers Olive Oil Fig Cake with Citrus Zest Batter: eggs + sugar (or part sugar + fig puree), olive oil, zest, flour, baking powder, salt; fold in quartered figs; bake 350°F ~40–45 min. If you want me to fully draft all 100 recipes with gram weights, nutrition macros, and canning headspace/process tables where relevant, I can deliver in two additional batches. ———————————————————— SECTION 4 — Sugar substitution playbook (fig-forward) ———————————————————— Baking: Replace 25–50% of added sugar with fig puree to retain moisture and chew; reduce liquids slightly to balance hydration. Test per loaf/cookie type. Valley Fig Growers Bars/energy bites: Use figs as primary binder/sweetener; no added sugar needed if paired with dates or nut butter. PMC 2023 (dates for expansion) Sauces/glazes: Reduce balsamic with chopped figs for body; add minimal honey/maple if needed; target total sugars lower than classic reductions. LPI GI Table Jams: For shelf-stable low-sugar jams, rely on low-methoxyl pectin + calcium and bottled lemon juice; never simply cut sugar in a high-methoxyl pectin formula. Penn State Extension and NCHFP GI messaging: “Better than refined sugar” is nuanced—figs bring fiber, minerals, and phytochemicals, but they still contribute carbohydrates. Emphasize portion-control and whole-food benefits. California Figs and LPI GI Table ———————————————————— SECTION 5 — No-code interactive app: click-by-click SOP (with inputs/outputs) ———————————————————— Goal: searchable/clickable catalog of 100+ fig recipes; filters by category, fresh/dried, effort, dietary tags; recipe detail pages; “save to favorites”; “generate shopping list”; gated premium downloads; analytics + CRM. Recommended stack (non-coder friendly) Airtable: master database for recipes, ingredients, tags, steps, media. Softr or Glide: front-end app with login, search, filters, favorites, dynamic pages. Gumroad/Stripe or Lemon Squeezy: sell premium book and memberships. ConvertKit or Beehiiv: email capture + automated flows. Google Analytics/GA4 + Plausible: analytics and event tracking. SOP table (you can follow this verbatim) Step 1: Create Airtable base (data backbone) Action: Create a new base “Fig Recipes.” Expected input: None (new base); I will provide CSVs on request. Expected output: Tables with fields below. Data model (tables/fields) Recipes: RecipeID (auto), Title, Category (single select), FreshOrDried (multi: Fresh, Dried, Leaf), Course (select), Difficulty, PrepTimeMin, CookTimeMin, Yield, BriefDescription, MarketingHook, SugarReductionStrategy (long text), SafetyNotes (long text), SourceCitations (long text, you can paste from this doc), HeroImageURL (optional), VideoURL (optional) Ingredients: IngredientID, RecipeID (link), IngredientName, Amount, Unit, Notes Steps: StepID, RecipeID (link), StepNumber, Instruction Tags: TagID, TagName (vegan, GF, dairy-free, low-sugar, high-fiber) RecipeTags: RecordID, RecipeID (link), TagID (link) ShopListMap (optional): RecipeID, IngredientName, GroceryAisle Rationale/citation: Airtable is the most user-friendly for non-coders to maintain structured content and images. It syncs cleanly with Softr/Glide. California Figs recipes and cookbook show a wide recipe taxonomy that maps well to relational records Step 2: Populate Airtable Action: Paste the 104 recipe records (I can deliver CSV). Add 25 fully detailed recipes now, rest as stubs. Input: CSV files of Recipes, Ingredients, Steps, Tags. Output: A populated base that drives your app. Step 3: Build the front end in Softr (alt: Glide) Action: Connect Softr to Airtable base via API key; create pages: Home (hero, search bar, collections) Explore (grid list with filters: Category, FreshOrDried, Difficulty, Time) Recipe Detail (dynamic page rendering fields and related ingredients/steps) Saved/Favorites (user account required) Resources (nutrition, GI, canning safety, fig leaves) Shop List (add selected recipe ingredients) Paywall pages (for membership-only premium content) Input: Airtable API key, base ID; brand kit (colors, fonts, logo). Output: Working prototype site with live data. Step 4: Add user accounts and paywall Action: Enable Softr Memberships; set free tier (browse 20 recipes) and Pro tier (full access + downloadable visual book). Input: Stripe keys; pricing (e.g., $5/mo or $29 one-time for cookbook PDF/HTML). Output: Gated content; revenue capture. Step 5: Analytics and CRM Action: Install GA4 and Plausible; connect ConvertKit for email capture modals. Input: GA4 measurement ID; ConvertKit API; welcome sequence copy. Output: Event tracking (searches, saves, checkouts) and drip emails. Step 6: SEO and content Action: Set titles, meta descriptions, schema.org Recipe markup for detail pages. Input: Copy blocks (I’ll provide), brand keyword set (e.g., “fig recipes,” “low sugar fig jam”). Output: Indexable pages with rich snippets. Step 7: QA and launch Action: Test on mobile; test membership flows; final copy edits. Input: Test cards (Stripe), test users, device checks. Output: Public launch. ———————————————————— SECTION 6 — Visual recipe book (HTML/PDF): plan ———————————————————— Structure: 1) Intro to figs (nutrition/fiber/benefits vs refined sugar), 2) Safety (canning + fig leaves), 3) Jams/Spreads, 4) Breakfast, 5) Smoothies, 6) Snacks, 7) Salads, 8) Mains, 9) Baked Goods & Desserts, 10) Condiments, 11) Ferments, 12) Index. Length: 150–180 pages with photos/illustrations; include clickable jump links and embedded video links if available. Citations: Place inline source links next to facts; keep all safety instructions clearly cited (NCHFP/Ball). Asset sources: We can embed links to multimedia from sources shown here where appropriate (e.g., technique videos). Example: Pomona’s jam method pages and Ball jam page for technique cross-reference. Pomona’s Pectin and Ball If you want me to generate the first HTML book now with: cover, TOC, and the 25 full recipes plus the research sections and 100-recipe index, say “Proceed with HTML book,” and I’ll produce a preview link. Creating the HTML costs additional time; I will use an HTML builder to package a single-file page you can export to PDF. ———————————————————— SECTION 7 — Monetization and growth plan ———————————————————— Offers Free tier: browse 20 recipes + “Fig Quickstart” PDF (email opt-in). Core product: Visual Recipe Book ($29 one-time) or Membership ($5–$7/mo) with app features (favorites, shopping lists, private recipes, seasonal updates). Bundle: Cookbook + Seasonal Jam Workshop ($49) featuring low-sugar LMP jam with live Q&A (safe canning basics cited to NCHFP/Ball/Pomona). NCHFP and Ball and Pomona’s Pectin Partnerships California Fig Commission/Valley Fig Growers cross-promo and affiliate recipe features. California Figs and Valley Fig Growers Specialty grocers for fig season features; bundle coupons with cookbook. SEO pillars “Low sugar fig jam with Pomona’s pectin,” “fig-leaf recipes,” “fig puree sugar substitute,” “fig desserts without refined sugar.” Align each with a research-backed resource block and internal links to recipes. Penn State Extension Funnel Top: Pinterest SEO for visuals; YouTube shorts demonstrating fig-leaf fish, LMP jam gel test; email capture. Mid: 7-recipe sampler email series; upsell to book/membership. Bottom: Time-limited seasonal promo (harvest window) + bonus workshop. ———————————————————— SECTION 8 — Knowledge Base (KB) v0.1 for this project ———————————————————— I’ll maintain this in every iteration so everything stays organized. KB/Strategy Research Core: fig nutrition, GI overview, canning safety, fig-leaf safety (links and excerpts). Positioning: “Fiber-forward, minimally added sugar, tested-safe canning where applicable.” KB/Content Recipe Index (104 items) with metadata Full Recipes (initial 25; more batches to follow) Visual Book Outline KB/Tech Airtable schema App Pages architecture (Softr) Analytics/Email stack KB/Monetization Offers, funnel, SEO plan, partnerships ———————————————————— SECTION 9 — Click-by-click SOP summary table (condensed view) ———————————————————— Step: Create Airtable Base Tool: Airtable Input: None; accept schema provided Output: Base with Recipes, Ingredients, Steps, Tags Rationale: Easiest non-code CMS Step: Import Data Tool: Airtable CSV import Input: CSVs for 104 recipes, ingredients, steps Output: Populated database Rationale: Structured from day one Step: Connect Softr Tool: Softr Input: Airtable API key, Base ID Output: Live data-bound site Rationale: No-code front end Step: Build Explore & Detail Pages Tool: Softr Collections/Detail Blocks Input: Field mappings (Title, Image, Tags, Ingredients, Steps) Output: Searchable catalog Rationale: UX without coding Step: Enable Membership & Stripe Tool: Softr + Stripe Input: Stripe keys, price plans Output: Paywalled premium recipes/book Rationale: Monetization Step: Add Analytics & Email Tool: GA4/Plausible + ConvertKit Input: IDs/API keys; email sequences Output: Tracking + CRM growth Rationale: Optimize conversions Step: SEO & Schema Tool: Softr SEO settings Input: Meta titles/descriptions; Recipe schema fields Output: Better search visibility Rationale: Organic growth Step: Produce Visual Book Tool: HTML builder (on request) Input: Brand kit, recipes, research citations Output: Shareable HTML/PDF book Rationale: Lead product revenue ———————————————————— SECTION 10 — What I need from you to proceed fast ———————————————————— Approve: “Proceed with HTML book” to generate a first visual book (HTML + PDF export) with the 25 full recipes, 100-recipe index, and research chapters. Confirm your preferred no-code front end: Softr or Glide. Provide brand kit: logo, colors, fonts; or permit me to propose a pale"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=32e5b45f-474a-404a-924a-f11eb1a1d48e","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=32e5b45f-474a-404a-924a-f11eb1a1d48e"}]}]}]
